In this work the artist is literally elevating snacks to a new level. Typically bowls, and vessels of this sort, sit directly on a table top - but here the artist raises it off the surface while also reducing the overall size of the vessel; a subtle commentary on portion size, and highlighting the graceful nature of the cascading vine fruits. The banana hook is higher still - aiding as a reminder that bananas grow on trees in distant lands and we should be cognizant of both the assets and liabilities of global farming infrastructures forged in the fires of imperialism. Finally, by employing the use of cobalt blue, a mineral found deep in the earth, we are grounded in gratitude towards the gifts of our planet, and reminded to cherish all that she produces. The power of snacks!

I would love a company to simply just say: We love what we’re making, and we think that it will add value to your life. And so we borrowed a lot of money to make this stuff, and we have to pay those people back. So we have to keep making and selling more stuff than we did yesterday because we live in a growth based economy and if we all stop the entire system will collapse. I mean, if you’re gonna leverage the anxiety of our own guilt and the fear of social repercussions, just go all the way to existential dread! But for now, perhaps we can talk about things and stuff in a more robust way than solutions for avoiding the trash. If you are more concerned about things when they are not being used anymore, then maybe don’t make them in the first place? Since when did Marketers become death doulas for product design? If matter matters, then why is there so much emphasis on when it doesn’t matter anymore? #designsermon

On the occasion of his newly released collab with @westelm I’m doing some light research on @colinking - the interior stylist that appears to be everywhere right now. As always, I’m interested in the language we use to build our constructs of architecture and interiors - as it tends to tie in with how we actually think about these spaces, and ourselves. I love this observation by writer @danielle_blundell because it points very astutely to a process in interiors that we often don’t see - the role of the stylist who is preparing the space to be photographed. Because it’s not really* about the interiors, it’s about the photographed version of the interiors. The stylized arrangement in service of photographic composition. The mediated interior for people who express their self through the mediation of their own interiors. And I totally agree with the sentiment in quote - it is the humility of the stylist (as product designer) that knows that no one piece can make a room, it’s the arranging of all the elements in harmony. It is precisely that sensibility that makes them good product designers - because it’s all about the space, not the product itself.

Hey @dominomag leave the TikTok trends on TikTok. No need to validate, much less promote and link knock-offs! We get it, Ad revenue is down, and Sam’s Club is paying you to generate content, but there has to be another way besides promoting white labeled junk! I will write you 2 articles a month for free until the end of the year. Let the social media lay people content creators do their thing - let them run towards the lowest common denominator - let them go after the dupes! We don’t need to help them! And the next time you sit down with the teams at Sam’s Club/Walmart let them know there is an entire generation of exceptional design talent sitting on thousands of ideas - and all they need is a manufacturing and sourcing partner (perhaps one of the best in the world?) to develop original, aspirational, and affordable pieces for their stores. Where have all the editors gone!?

Speaking of Anthropologie, they were the first retailer to carry my Rod+Weave Chair. As the story goes, I skipped my thesis show and graduation ceremony from my Master's program to show my work in NYC for design week in 2013. I was lucky enough to showcase my work with @_sightunseen_  and @designmilk . Some buyer from Anthro came to the show (not sure which one) and emailed me the next day to place an order for 10 chairs - 5 in each color. I felt immediately vindicated for skipping my school “obligations” (I mean, who’s paying who?) as my program was called Applied Craft & Design, I felt like I was actually applying Craft and Design!!! Anyway, the chairs went live in the Spring of '14, we're 50% off within a month or two, and a reorder never came through. That's it. I don't think I have a point to this story. I just felt like looking up these chairs to see if I can find the original Anthro images - their photography styling hasn't changed!

About 10-12 years ago @matthewphilipwilliams @wc_rueck and I, came up with a theory that is a helpful way to talk about chairs in relationship to sitting time. For a chair to be a chair, you must be able to sit on it, but for how long? Therefore we started classifying chairs by how long an average adult could sit in one. And that’s how we classified each others chairs too. And there is some correlation to the categories of chairs too, lounge, occasional, side, dining, etc..

Art-Oriented-Products or Artist-Oriented-Products or AOPs for short. One of my professors once said, the first thing I look for in a piece is “what is the commitment?” If the messaging around your products is the value added because YOU made (or designed) them, then that is an AOP. This approach starts with the thing - and then needs to go find the market. Versus making a thing to fit the market. #ataxonomyofdesign

Like a drive through the desert hours after a winter rain.
The way the air hangs low, maybe even a little thick. 
You can feel it. 
It's like walking through a fog cloud, but it's not a cloud because the sky is clear now - the rain grabbed all the dust, and ozone, and nitrogen, and slammed into the thirsty ground.
It's the water, and the soil, and now something coming up from the cracks, hovering for a few days. 
You ask your kid - can you smell that? What is that coming up from the ground? 
She retorts, "It smells like the Earth's breath!" in almost a cackly laugh. She's clever, and she knows it. But it's perfect. 
This fragrance smells like the Earth is breathing, and you set up a hammock in its sigh.

Ok, here’s another avenue in the product world - the BOP! Often times, these start-ups are leveraging the credibility of the CEO too. Like in the case of Burrow - the founders are graduates of Wharton. A lot of times, these businesses confuse product features for benefits. Such as “cut to size” or “assembled in seconds” - because at the end of the day, the business itself is the product it is selling to investors versus, selling products to customers. Regardless, the founders story has nothing to do with the success of the actual product in the real world. Stay tuned for a breakdown on UOPs!!! #designsermon

There are a spectrum of “resins” out there. Some of which are not even available in the U.S. Time to get a bit more granular here. What kind of resin? With the large retailers, I’m seeing a lot of resin decorative accessories - the stuff that used to be made in ceramic or glass. It’s now cast in resin and painted. It’s junk. But I’m also seeing it with a lot of small maker based studios, to varying qualities and applications. What’s up with resin? It seems more like a DIY/Craft material - something you do for yourself, not to resale to others, no?
A little riff on resin products, and a statement for the Artists.

Reflection: I often wonder if Christianity didn’t become the state religion of the Roman Empire, if the cross ever would have become the symbol it is today? The cross never shows up in early Christian art. It’s not until Constantine has a vision “in this sign conquer” that he has all his troops paint their shields with a cross, and they win the battle. Superstition + Coincidence = Divine Intervention?  Such an odd move from where it started - a first century Rabbi is so threatening to the empire and religious establishment that he is tortured and hung on a cross to die. And then 400 years later, that very same imperial torture device becomes the symbol of that religion? The amount of hoop-jumping theologizing one has to do to have that make sense will never stop boggling my mind. Regardless, when I encounter great architecture in Christian spaces, I always get bummed about the fidelity to the icon/logo of the cross. And for you religion nerds, it’s double baffling, since substitutionary atonement wasn’t invented for another millennia. 🧐

Gosh dang this is perfect @for____scale !!! // That’s the whole jam, y’all. I like you, because you’re like me, and I like me, so I like you. That is art. That is love. That is finding a fast friend. That’s the magic. Of all the categories of things, and sizes and shapes, and colors - there are just an infinite amount of combinations. What makes life in the age of infinite everyThing meaningful? Choice. 
 
And I think consumption maturity arrives when trends are adopted as they are in alignment with oneself, rather than aligning oneself with the market. I love waiting for the market to come to me.
Personally, I live in a “buyers market” - and I want you to, as well. 
Business-wise, it is my job to do everything I can to leverage the atmosphere of a buyers market within the transaction. Everyone feels better that way.

social_posts.post_text: Always a great joy to be able to personally deliver orders to customers. I love houses and furniture and families and parents and kids and all the stuff and all the things that come in and out of our spaces which we use to articulate and activate the way in which we move through our physical spaces as physical people. This couple had been “coveting these chairs since they saw them in a shop in Chicago.” This is what I love about making stuff. Of all the possible versions of a chair I could make, I made this one - and someone saw it in a space in Chicago and connected with it. And they connected with it enough for it to stay in the “vision board” of their mind. What a lovely occurrence that the space and time that I happen to be making stuff aligns with the space and time these folks happen to be living too. It reminds me of that note from @for____scale that I posted the other day - about a “cosmic alignment between strangers” - that can seem a little woo, but it’s also present within every day exchanges - in this case, a chair being a document of a cosmic connection. No need to elevate anything, it’s all already there.

Design after Divorce will definitely be a chapter in my book. It’s not a chapter I was planning to write, ever, and yet, here we are. (Which, of course, is all we ever really are). 
I've hesitated to share this because 1, I do not like performative vulnerability on social, (that’s what the actual physical humans in your life are for, they hug back.) and 2. Just the economics and power dynamics (that are outside of me, but I no less contribute to) when I share something like this. 
AND I’ve also felt super seen when other folks share what’s going on IRL, that we don’t see on IG. The human stuff, that we ALL can connect to. It's just a tricky thing to share, without it seeming performative or like I'm capitalizing on the pain of life.
And then I thought further - and largely, my output is just that - being WITH the pain of life - AND THEN providing opportunity and resources to ease that pain, or walk around it, or just sit with it, and unpack it, or go deeper with it. And I’m doing that all the time, because I’m an artist - so I bring ideas into form so I can walk around them and feel them, and share them. 
And sometimes that idea becomes a product and participates in an economic exchange - like kitchen stools, or wall hooks, or providing interior design services, or consulting on how to change your coffee routine so you can do a 10 min HIIT circuit before your kids even wake up. Or simply sharing with you on this slick surface, “the cracks are where the light gets in” - I’m full of cracks. They are beautiful, and yours are too. 

With the confidence that comes with midlife, I mean this: I CAN ADD VALUE HERE.
Dads, what are your pain points? Kitchen? Bathrooms? Routines? Bedtimes? Mattress density? 
Folks in relationships with Dad (partners, kids, etc) - what are Dad's blindspots that he could use some help with? 
Bonus Extra Credit Reflective question - Are Dad's "blindspots" more about your expectations of them, or about equipping them with what they need to thrive?
I don’t say it enough, I love you all, and I’m grateful for you. 
✌️❤️🌵

Dinglehoppering - The process of re-narrating existing forms via convincing alternative utility. 
“Dinglehoppers” are a cornerstone of my studio practice and output. One of the things I’m most excited about for @thephysicalshop is having a place to serialize these ideas into accessible products.
I think a central motivator in this exchange, is that I like to make things that someone else will finish, or take further, or do something different with (furniture, interiors, playground, public art, group performance art therapy with pool noodles). 

A call and response, exercised through an exchange of physical product, producing a ripple effect, philosophically; as the idea embedded in the object, is greater than the object itself. (1+1=3). 
To engage with this product, is to practice a different orientation to the physical world. 
Thus is the goal of dinglehoppering - to transcend aesthetic, via personal narrative - revealed via utility, and exercised with delight. 
#dinglehoppery

Most mornings I relay emails about these kitchen stools, while sitting in my kitchen, on the same stools. 
Most of the time I’m emailing with a couple who have either just moved in, are about to move in, renovating, or about to renovate. I say that because I’ve found that these stools (or any) are often connected to a vision - “when we finish the kitchen I want these stools at the island or counter”
“We’ve been waiting to buy your stools until we bought a house”
“We’re planning to have kids soon…”
“Our kids are young, how do these work with kids as they grow?” 
Or a recent one “I’ve been SCOURING the internet trying to find your stools” (because I haven’t been doing a great job running this biz for a few years 😵‍💫). 

Yes AND - This is my favorite part of the intertwangle-ism of a craft oriented life - is that my life looks a lot like the lives of my customers and vice versa. But I also see all the things I’ve bought from other people who make different things than I make. 
And I can tell you what it’s like to live with these stools, as an adult, with kids 1-10 years old, as they grow up, with people over 60 sitting in them (hi mom and dad) - you know just the ordinary life of a kitchen stool - that I love with, in my life. 
So while I do work in “Design” I still find a greater kinship with a Craft orientation. And I like Ralph Caplan’s definition the best - “I made this for me, and therefore for you.”
And I can also tell you that the @bzippy brutalist vase is my favorite for droopy tulips, my @all_roads_studio kitchen towels are the only ones I use now, my petite @heatherrosenmanceramics bud vase that reminds me that I need more of her work in my life, my @dion_ceramics mugs are perfect and if I had a million dollars I would start a business just to make those forever. I love all the things, all the time, and I’m never gonna stop talking about it 😎.

Oh, and $2 ceramic flush mounts, with mirror globe G40 is quite possibly the most perfect lighting for a low ceiling house (just put them on a dimmer, and get longer mounting screws if your jbox is oddly recessed 🙃).
